    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Supernovae (SNe) have significant impact on their surroundings, and are strong candidates for explaining the large dust masses seen in the early universe. However, observations of dust in SNe fall short of theoretical predictions, though supernova remnants show larger dust masses. Molecules are intimately linked with dust formation, and CO and SiO are observed in SNe soon after the explosion. Molecules chemically control the onset, composition, and mass of SN dust. Some molecules, such as SiO, are dust precursors, while others, like CO, do not get incorporated in the dust. Recently, CO and SiO has been observed in SN 1987A. Chemical kinetic modeling predicts that other molecules should also be present in the ejecta. Based on these model predictions and the excitation conditions in the ejecta of SN 1987A, SiS and SO, in particular, should have bright emission lines at mm wavelengths. We propose to scan two spectral windows, in ALMA B3 and B4, focusing on these species, in order to probe the chemistry and physical conditions in the ejecta. Our observations will also include isotopologues of SiS and SO, allowing us to probe the nucleosynthesis of sulfur and silicon. 
</prp:abstract>
